# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: csa-group
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:csa-group/agmark] The term agmark was coined by joining the words 'Ag' to mean agriculture and 'mark' for a certification mark.
[src:csa-group/agmark] This term was introduced originally in the bill presented in the parliament of India for the *Agricultural Produce (Grading and Marking) Act*.
[src:csa-group/agmark] The entire system of Agmark, including the name, was created by Archibald MacDonald Livingstone, Agricultural and Marketing Advisory to the Government of India, from 1934 to 1941.
[src:csa-group/agmark] He was supported by a staff of several hundred.
[src:csa-group/agmark] The system was designed to benefit local growers throughout India who were, in the absence of a certification as to quality, exposed to receiving less for their produce from dealers than its true worth.
[src:csa-group/agmark] The Agmark certification is employed through fully state-owned Agmark laboratories located across the nation which act as testing and certifying centres.
[src:csa-group/agmark] In addition to the *Central AGMARK Laboratory (CAL)* in Nagpur, there are *Regional AGMARK Laboratories (RALs)* in 11 nodal cities (Mumbai, New Delhi, Chennai, Kolkata, Kanpur, Kochi, Guntur, Amritsar, Jaipur, Rajkot, Bhopal).
[src:csa-group/agmark] Each of the regional laboratories is equipped with and specializes in the testing of products of regional significance.
[src:csa-group/agmark] Hence the product range that could be tested varies across the centres.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia shares the landmass of Eurasia with Europe, and of Afro-Eurasia with both Europe and Africa.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In general terms, it is bounded on the east by the Pacific Ocean, on the south by the Indian Ocean, and on the north by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The border of Asia with Europe is a historical and cultural construct, as there is no clear physical and geographical separation between them.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] A commonly accepted division places Asia to the east of the Suez Canal separating it from Africa; and to the east of the Turkish straits, the Ural Mountains and Ural River, and to the south of the Caucasus Mountains and the Caspian and Black seas, separating it from Europe.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Since the concept of Asia derives from the term for the eastern region from a European perspective, Asia is the remaining vast area of Eurasia minus Europe.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Therefore, Asia is a region where various independent cultures coexist rather than sharing a single culture, and its boundary with Europe is somewhat arbitrary and has moved since its first conception in classical antiquity.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The division of Eurasia into two continents reflects East–West cultural differences, some of which vary on a spectrum.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] China and India traded places as the largest economies in the world from 1 to 1800 CE.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] China was a major economic power for much of recorded history, with the highest GDP per capita until 1500.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Silk Road became the main east–west trading route in the Asian hinterlands while the Straits of Malacca stood as a major sea route.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia has exhibited economic dynamism as well as robust population growth during the 20th century, but overall population growth has since fallen.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia was the birthplace of most of the world's mainstream religions including Islam, Judaism, Christianity, Hinduism, Buddhism, and many other religions.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia varies greatly across and within its regions with regard to ethnic groups, cultures, environments, economics, historical ties, and government systems.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The term "Asia" is believed to originate in the Bronze Age toponym *Assuwa* (Hittite: 𒀸𒋗𒉿, romanized: *aš-šu-wa*) which originally referred only to a portion of northwestern Anatolia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The term appears in Hittite records recounting how a confederation of Assuwan states including Troy unsuccessfully rebelled against the Hittite king Tudhaliya I around 1400 BCE.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Roughly contemporary Linear B documents contain the term *aswia* (Mycenaean Greek: 𐀀𐀯𐀹𐀊, romanized: *a-si-wi-ja*), seemingly in reference to captives from the same area.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Herodotus used the term in reference to Anatolia and the territory of the Achaemenid Empire, in contrast to Greece and Egypt.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] He reports that Greeks assumed that Asia was named after the wife of Prometheus, but that Lydians say it was named after *Asies*, son of Cotys, who passed the name on to a tribe at Sardis.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In Greek mythology, "Asia" (Ἀσία or Ἀσίη) was the name of a "Nymph or Titan goddess of Lydia".
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Iliad (attributed by the ancient Greeks to Homer) mentions two Phrygians in the Trojan War named Asios (literally 'Asian'); and also a marsh or lowland containing a marsh in Lydia as ασιος.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The term was later adopted by the Romans, who used it in reference to the province of Asia, located in western Anatolia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] One of the first writers to use Asia as a name of the whole continent was Pliny.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The threefold division of the Old World into Africa, Asia, and Europe has been in use since the 6th century BCE, due to Greek geographers such as Anaximander and Hecataeus.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Anaximander placed the boundary between Asia and Europe along the Phasis River (now the Rioni) in Georgia of Caucasus (from its mouth by Poti on the Black Sea coast, through the Surami Pass and along the Kura River to the Caspian Sea), a convention still followed by Herodotus in the 5th century BCE.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] During the Hellenistic period, this convention was revised, and the boundary between Europe and Asia was now considered to be the Tanais (the modern Don River).
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] This is the convention used by Roman era authors such as Posidonius, Strabo and Ptolemy.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The border between Asia and Europe was later redefined by European academics.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In 1730, five years after the death of Peter the Great, Philip Johan von Strahlenberg published in Sweden a new atlas proposing the Ural Mountains as the border of Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Vasily Tatishchev announced that he had proposed the idea to von Strahlenberg.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The latter had suggested the Emba River as the southern part of this boundary.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Over the next century various proposals were made until the Ural River prevailed in the mid-19th century.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The border had been moved perforce from the Black Sea (the Romans' definition) to the Caspian Sea into which the Emba and Ural rivers project.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Between the Black Sea and the Caspian, the border is often placed along the crest of the Caucasus Mountains, although it is sometimes placed further north, on the Kuma–Manych Depression.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The boundary between Asia and Africa is the Suez Canal, the Gulf of Suez, the Red Sea, and the Bab-el-Mandeb.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] This makes Egypt a transcontinental country, with the Sinai Peninsula in Asia and the remainder of the country in Africa.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The border between Asia and Oceania is usually placed somewhere in the Indonesian Archipelago, specifically in Eastern Indonesia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Wallace Line separates the Asian and Wallacea biogeographical realms, a transition zone of deep water straits between the Asian and Australian continental shelves.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Weber's Line split the region in two with regard to the balance of fauna between Asian origin or Australo-Papuan origin.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Wallacea's eastern boundary with Sahul is represented by the Lydekker's Line.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Maluku Islands (except the Aru Islands) are often considered to lie on the border of southeast Asia, with the Aru Islands and Western New Guinea, to the east of the Lydekker's Line, being wholly part of Oceania, as both lie on the Australian continental plate.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Culturally, the Wallacea region denoted the transition between Austronesian and Melanesian people, with varying degrees of intermixing between the two.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In general, the further west and coastal a region is, the stronger the Austronesian influences, and the further east and inland a region is, the stronger the Melanesian influences.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The terms Southeast Asia and Oceania, devised in the 19th century, have had several vastly different geographic meanings since their inception.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The chief factor in determining which islands of the Indonesian Archipelago are Asian has been the location of the colonial possessions of the various empires there (not all European).
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Bering Strait and Bering Sea separate the landmasses of Asia and North America, as well as forming the international boundary between Russia and the United States.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] This national and continental boundary separates the Diomede Islands in the Bering Strait, with Big Diomede in Russia and Little Diomede in the United States.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Aleutian Islands are an island chain extending westward from the Alaskan Peninsula toward Russia's Komandorski Islands and Kamchatka Peninsula.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Aleutian Islands are sometimes associated with Oceania, owing to their status as remote Pacific islands, and their proximity to the Pacific Plate.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] This is extremely rare however, due to their non-tropical biogeography, as well as their inhabitants, who have historically been related to the Indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Lawrence Island in the northern Bering Sea belongs to the US state of Alaska and may be associated with either continent but is almost always considered part of North America, as with the Rat Islands in the Aleutian chain.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] At their nearest points, Alaska and Russia are separated by only 4 kilometres (2.5 miles).
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Geographical Asia is a cultural artifact of European conceptions of the world, beginning with the Ancient Greeks, being imposed onto other cultures, an imprecise concept causing endemic contention about what it means.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia does not exactly correspond to the cultural borders of its various types of constituents.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] From the time of Herodotus, a minority of geographers have rejected the three-continent system (Europe, Africa, Asia) on the grounds that there is no substantial physical separation between them.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] For example, Sir Barry Cunliffe, the emeritus professor of European archeology at Oxford, argues that Europe has been geographically and culturally merely "the western excrescence of the continent of Asia".
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Geographically, Asia is the major eastern constituent of the continent of Eurasia with Europe being a northwestern peninsula of the landmass.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia, Europe and Africa make up a single continuous landmass—Afro-Eurasia—and share a common continental shelf.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Almost all of Europe and a major part of Asia sit atop the Eurasian Plate, adjoined on the south by the Arabian and Indian Plate and with the easternmost part of Siberia (east of the Chersky Range) on the North American Plate.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] About 1.8 million years ago, *Homo erectus* left the African continent.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] This species is believed to have lived in East and Southeast Asia from 1.8 million to 110,000 years ago.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Researchers believe that the modern human, or *Homo sapiens*, migrated about 60,000 years ago to South Asia along the Indian Ocean.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Modern humans interbred with an archaic human species called Denisovans in Southeast Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Before the arrival of modern humans, Flores was occupied by *Homo floresiensis*, a small archaic human.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Ancestors of East Eurasians split from Ancient West Eurasians about 46,000 years ago, migrating out of the hub in the Iranian Plateau.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The history of Asia can be seen as the distinct histories of several peripheral coastal regions: East Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, Central Asia, and West Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The coastal periphery was home to some of the world's earliest known civilisations, each of them developing around fertile river valleys.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The civilisations in Mesopotamia, the Indus Valley and the Yellow River shared many similarities.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] These civilisations may well have exchanged technologies and ideas such as mathematics and the wheel.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Other innovations, such as writing, seem to have been developed individually in each area.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Cities, states and empires developed in these lowlands.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The central steppe region had long been inhabited by horse-mounted nomads who could reach all areas of Asia from the steppes.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The earliest postulated expansion out of the steppe is that of the Indo-Europeans, who spread their languages into West Asia, South Asia, and the borders of China, where the Tocharians resided.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The northernmost part of Asia, including much of Siberia, was largely inaccessible to the steppe nomads, owing to the dense forests, climate and tundra.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] These areas remained very sparsely populated.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The center and the peripheries were mostly kept separated by mountains and deserts.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Caucasus and Himalaya mountains and the Karakum and Gobi deserts formed barriers that the steppe horsemen could cross only with difficulty.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] While the urban city dwellers were more advanced technologically and socially, in many cases they could do little in a military aspect to defend against the mounted hordes of the steppe.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] However, the lowlands did not have enough open grasslands to support a large equestrian force; for this and other reasons, the nomads who conquered states in China, India, and the Middle East often found themselves adapting to the local, more affluent societies.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Mongol Empire conquered a large part of Asia in the 13th century, an area extending from China to Europe.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Before the Mongol invasion, Song dynasty reportedly had approximately 120 million citizens; the 1300 census which followed the invasion reported roughly 60 million people.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Black Death, one of the most devastating pandemics in human history, is thought to have originated in the arid plains of central Asia, where it then travelled along the Silk Road.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] European involvement in Asia became more significant from the Age of Discovery onward, with Iberian-sponsored sailors such as Christopher Columbus and Vasco da Gama paving the way for new routes from Atlantic Europe to Pacific Asia and the Indian Ocean respectively in the late 15th century.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Russian Empire also began to expand into northwestern Asia from the 17th century, and would eventually take control of all of Siberia and most of Central Asia by the end of the 19th century.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Among non-European empires, the Ottoman Empire controlled Anatolia, most of the Middle East, North Africa and the Balkans from the mid 16th century onward, while in the 17th century, the Manchu conquered China and established the Qing dynasty.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Islamic Mughal Empire (preceded by the Delhi Sultanate of the 13th to early 16th century) and the Hindu Maratha Empire controlled much of India in the 16th and 18th centuries respectively.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Western imperialism in Asia from the 18th to 20th centuries coincided with the Industrial Revolution in the West and the dethroning of India and China as the world's foremost economies.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Around this time, Western powers started to dominate China in what later became known as the century of humiliation, with the British-supported opium trade and later Opium Wars resulting in China being forced into an unprecedented situation of importing more than it exported.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] One significant influence on Japan had been the United States, which had begun projecting influence across the Pacific after its early-to-mid-19th century westward expansion.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The breakup of the Ottoman Empire in the early 20th century led to the Middle East also being contested and partitioned by the British and French.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] With the end of World War II in 1945 and the wartime ruination of Europe and imperial Japan, many countries in Asia were able to rapidly free themselves of colonial rule.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The independence of India came along with the carving out of a separate nation for the majority of South Asian Muslims, which in 1971 further split into Pakistan and Bangladesh; The Cold War in Asia strained relations between India and Pakistan and affected Asia more generally.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The end of the Cold War and the Soviet Union by 1991 saw the independence of the five modern Central Asian countries.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Some Arab countries took economic advantage of massive oil deposits that were discovered in their territory, becoming globally influential, though stability in the Middle East has been affected since 1948 by the Arab–Israeli conflict and American-led interventions.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] East Asian nations (along with Singapore in Southeast Asia) became economically prosperous with high-growth "tiger economies"; China, having undergone the reform and opening up under Deng Xiaoping, regained its place among the top two economies of the world by the 21st century.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] It covers 9% of the Earth's total surface area (or 30% of its land area), and has the longest coastline, at 62,800 kilometres (39,022 mi).
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia is generally defined as comprising the eastern four-fifths of Eurasia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] It is located to the east of the Suez Canal and the Ural Mountains, and south of the Caucasus Mountains (or the Kuma–Manych Depression) and the Caspian and Black Seas.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] It is bounded on the east by the Pacific Ocean, on the south by the Indian Ocean and on the north by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia is subdivided into 49 countries, five of them (Georgia, Azerbaijan, Russia, Kazakhstan and Turkey) are transcontinental countries lying partly in Europe.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Geographically, Russia is partly and mostly in Asia, but is considered a European nation, both culturally and politically.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Gobi Desert is in Mongolia and the Arabian Desert stretches across much of the Middle East.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Yangtze in China is the longest river in the continent.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The Himalayas between Nepal and China is the tallest mountain range in the world.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Tropical rainforests stretch across much of southern Asia and coniferous and deciduous forests lie farther north.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Between 1990 and 2000 the area of primary forest in Asia decreased by 1.06 million hectares per year, between 2000 and 2015 it decreased by 280 000 ha per year.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] There are various approaches to the regional division of Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The following subdivision into regions is used, among others, by the United Nations Statistics Division (UNSD).
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] This division of Asia into regions by the United Nations is done solely for statistical reasons and does not imply any assumption about political or other affiliations of countries and territories.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia has extremely diverse climate features.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Climates range from Arctic and subarctic in Siberia to tropical in southern India and Southeast Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] It is moist across southeast sections, and dry across much of the interior.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Some of the largest daily temperature ranges on Earth occur in western sections of Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The monsoon circulation dominates across southern and eastern sections, due to the presence of the Himalayas forcing the formation of a thermal low which draws in moisture during the summer.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Southwestern sections of the continent are hot.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Siberia is one of the coldest places in the Northern Hemisphere, and can act as a source of arctic air masses for North America.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The most active place on Earth for tropical cyclone activity lies northeast of the Philippines and south of Japan.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Climate change is particularly important in Asia, as the continent accounts for the majority of the human population.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Warming since the 20th century is increasing the threat of heatwaves across the entire continent.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Heatwaves lead to increased mortality, and the demand for air conditioning is rapidly accelerating as the result.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] By 2080, around 1 billion people in the cities of South and Southeast Asia are expected to experience around a month of extreme heat every year.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The impacts on water cycle are more complicated: already arid regions, primarily located in West Asia and Central Asia, will see more droughts, while areas of East, Southeast and South Asia which are already wet due to the monsoons will experience more flooding.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The waters around Asia are subjected to the same impacts as elsewhere, such as the increased warming and ocean acidification.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] There are many coral reefs in the region, and they are highly vulnerable to climate change, to the point practically all of them will be lost if the warming exceeds 1.5 °C (2.7 °F).
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia's distinctive mangrove ecosystems are also highly vulnerable to sea level rise.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia also has more countries with large coastal populations than any other continent, which would cause large economic impacts from sea level rise.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Water supplies in the Hindu Kush region will become more unstable as its enormous glaciers, known as the "Asian water towers", gradually melt.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] These changes to water cycle also affect vector-borne disease distribution, with malaria and dengue fever expected to become more prominent in the tropical and subtropical regions.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Food security will become more uneven, and South Asian countries could experience significant impacts from global food price volatility.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Historical emissions from Asia are lower than those from Europe and North America.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] However, China has been the single largest emitter of greenhouse gases in the 21st century, while India is the third-largest.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] As a whole, Asia currently accounts for 36% of world's primary energy consumption, which is expected to increase to 48% by 2050.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] By 2040, it is also expected to account for 80% of the world's coal and 26% of the world's natural gas consumption.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] While the United States remains the world's largest oil consumer, by 2050 it is projected to move to third place, behind China and India.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] While nearly half of the world's new renewable energy capacity is built in Asia, this is not yet sufficient in order to meet the goals of the Paris Agreement.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] They imply that the renewables would account for 35% of total energy consumption in Asia by 2030.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Climate change adaptation is already a reality for many Asian countries, with a wide range of strategies attempted across the continent.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Important examples include the growing implementation of climate-smart agriculture in certain countries or the "sponge city" planning principles in China.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] While some countries have drawn up extensive frameworks such as the Bangladesh Delta Plan or Japan's Climate Adaptation Act, others still rely on localized actions that are not effectively scaled up.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The most democratic countries in Asia are Japan, Taiwan and South Korea according to the V-Dem Democracy indices.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Within the states mentioned above are several partially recognized countries with limited to no international recognition.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia is both the largest continental economy in the world by both GDP nominal and PPP values and the world's fastest growing economic region.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] As of 2026, China is by far the largest economy on the continent.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] It is followed by India, Japan, South Korea, Turkey, Indonesia, Saudi Arabia, and Taiwan, which are all ranked among the top 20 largest economies by both nominal GDP and PPP values.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Based on Global Office Locations 2011, Asia dominated global office locations with 4 of the top 5 being in Asia: Hong Kong, Singapore, Tokyo and Seoul.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Around 68% of international firms have an office in Hong Kong.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In the late 1990s and early 2000s, the economy of China had an average annual growth rate of more than 8%.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] According to economic historian Angus Maddison, India had the world's largest economy for much of the past three millennia prior to the 19th century, accounting for 25% of the world's industrial output.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] China was the largest and most advanced economy on Earth for much of recorded history and shared the mantle with India.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] For several decades in the late twentieth century, Japan was the largest economy in Asia and second-largest in the world, after surpassing the Soviet Union (measured in net material product) in 1990 and Germany in 1968.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] This ended in 2010, when China overtook Japan to become the world's second largest economy.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In 2025, India overtook Japan in terms of nominal GDP to become the world's 4th largest and Asia's 2nd largest economy.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In the late 1980s and early 1990s, Japan's GDP by currency exchange rates was almost as large as that of the rest of Asia combined.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In 1995, Japan's economy nearly equaled that of the US as the largest economy in the world for a day, after the Japanese currency reached a record high of 79 yen/US$.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Economic growth in Asia since World War II to the 1990s had been concentrated in Japan as well as South Korea, Taiwan, Hong Kong, and Singapore, known as the Four Asian Tigers, which are now all considered developed economies, having among the highest GDP per capita in Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia is the largest continent in the world by a considerable margin, and it is rich in natural resources, such as petroleum, forests, fish, water, rice, copper and silver.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Manufacturing in Asia has traditionally been strongest in East and Southeast Asia, particularly in China, Taiwan, South Korea, Japan, India, the Philippines, and Singapore.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Japan and South Korea continue to dominate in the area of multinational corporations, though increasingly China and India are making significant inroads.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Many companies from Europe, North America, South Korea, and Japan have operations in Asia's developing countries to take advantage of its abundant supply of cheap labour and relatively developed infrastructure.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] According to Citigroup in 2011, 9 of 11 Global Growth Generator countries came from Asia driven by population and income growth.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] They are Bangladesh, China, India, Indonesia, Iraq, Mongolia, the Philippines, Sri Lanka, and Vietnam.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia has three main financial centers: Hong Kong, Tokyo, and Singapore.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Call centers and business process outsourcing firms (BPOs) are becoming major employers in India and the Philippines due to the availability of a large pool of highly skilled, English-speaking workers.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The increased use of outsourcing has assisted the rise of India and the China as financial centers.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Due to its large and extremely competitive information technology industry, India has become a major hub for outsourcing.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Trade between Asian countries and countries on other continents is largely carried out via sea routes.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] A far smaller part of the goods traffic runs via South Africa to Europe.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] A particularly significant part of Asian goods traffic is carried out on the Pacific Rim, toward Los Angeles and Long Beach.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The melting of the Arctic is also paving the way for new shipping routes from Northeast Asia to Europe and North America.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The land route to Europe is also the subject of construction projects, comparatively smaller in scope.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Intra-Asian trade, including sea trade, is growing rapidly.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In 2010, Asia had 3.3 million millionaires (people with net worth over US$1 million excluding their homes), slightly below North America's 3.4 million.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In 2011, Asia topped Europe in the number of millionaires.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Citigroup in The Wealth Report 2012 stated that the total wealth of people in Asia with over $100 million in assets exceeded that of their North American counterparts for the first time, as the world's "economic center of gravity" continued moving east.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] At the end of 2011, there were 18,000 people in Asia, mainly in Southeast Asia, China, and Japan, with at least $100 million in disposable assets, compared to North America with 17,000 and Western Europe with 14,000.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Asia's electricity demand has quadrupled since 2000 (rising from 4,199 TWh to over 16,000 TWh in 2024).
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] This growth, driven largely by China and increasingly by India, Indonesia, and Viet Nam, makes Asia the fastest-growing region for electricity demand globally, at about 5% per year.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] The region now accounts for about 36% of global primary energy consumption, a share projected to approach 50% by 2050.: 1468 Fossil fuels remain central in Asia: 66% of its energy is generated from fossil fuels, and Asia makes up 83% of the world's coal generation.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] However, coal is slowly being phased out and natural gas is displacing oil and oil products in various sectors, supported by policies and regulations.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] Natural gas demand in emerging market and developing economies in Asia expanded by around 6% in 2024, accounting for nearly 40% of incremental global gas demand.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] At the same time, Asia is the global leader in renewable energy expansion.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] It is currently the only region on track to meet the goal of tripling renewable capacity by 2030, largely due to China, the leading nation in renewable energy generation.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] China's wind and solar capacity has surged in recent years, together overtaking that of coal, while in 2024 India become the world's third largest generator of electricity from wind and solar.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] In 2013, with regional tourism growing and dominated by Chinese visitors, MasterCard released the Global Destination Cities Index report, in which 10 of 20 cities are Asian and Pacific cities.
[src:csa-group/asia-p01] This was also the first time an Asian city (Bangkok) was in the number one spot, with 15.98 million international visitors.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] East Asia had by far the strongest overall Human Development Index (HDI) improvement of any region in the world, nearly doubling average HDI attainment over the past 40 years, according to the report's analysis of health, education and income data.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] China, the second highest achiever in the world in terms of HDI improvement since 1970, is the only country on the "Top 10 Movers" list due to income rather than health or education achievements.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Its per capita income increased a stunning 21-fold over the last four decades, also lifting hundreds of millions out of income poverty.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Yet it was not among the region's top performers in improving school enrollment and life expectancy.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Nepal, a South Asian country, emerges as one of the world's fastest movers since 1970 mainly due to health and education achievements.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Its present life expectancy is 25 years longer than in the 1970s.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] More than four of every five children of school age in Nepal now attend primary school, compared to just one in five 40 years ago.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Hong Kong ranked highest among the countries grouped on the HDI (number 7 in the world, which is in the "very high human development" category), followed by Singapore (9), Japan (19) and South Korea (22).
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Afghanistan (155) ranked lowest amongst Asian countries out of the 169 countries assessed.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Asia is home to several language families and many language isolates.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Most Asian countries have more than one language that is natively spoken.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] For instance, according to Ethnologue, more than 700 languages are spoken in Indonesia, more than 400 languages spoken in India, and more than 100 are spoken in the Philippines.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] China has many languages and dialects in different provinces.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Many of the world's major religions have their origins in Asia, including the five most practiced in the world (excluding irreligion), which are Christianity, Islam, Hinduism, Chinese folk religion (classified as Confucianism and Taoism), and Buddhism.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The story of the Great Flood for example, as presented to Jews in the Hebrew Bible in the narrative of Noah—and later to Christians in the Old Testament, and to Muslims in the Quran—is earliest found in Mesopotamian mythology, in the Enûma Eliš and *Epic of Gilgamesh*.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Hindu mythology similarly tells about an avatar of Vishnu in the form of a fish who warned Manu of a terrible flood.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Ancient Chinese mythology also tells of a Great Flood spanning generations, one that required the combined efforts of emperors and divinities to control.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The Abrahamic religions including Judaism, Christianity, Islam, Druze faith, and Baháʼí Faith originated in West Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Jews are the predominant ethnic group in Israel (75.6%) numbering at about 6.1 million, although the levels of adherence to Jewish religion vary.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Outside of Israel there are small ancient Jewish communities in Turkey (17,400), Azerbaijan (9,100), Iran (8,756), India (5,000) and Uzbekistan (4,000), among many other places.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] As of 2016, there are am estimated 14.4–17.5 million (2016, est.) Jews alive in the world today, making them one of the smallest Asian minorities, at roughly 0.3–0.4& of the total population of the continent.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Christianity is a widespread religion in Asia, with more than 286 million adherents in 2010 according to Pew Research Center, and nearly 364 million according to Britannica Book of the Year 2014.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Christians constitute around 12.6% of the total population of Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] In the Philippines and Timor-Leste, Catholicism is the predominant religion; it was introduced by the Spaniards and the Portuguese, respectively.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] In Armenia and Georgia, Eastern Orthodoxy is the predominant religion.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] In the Middle East, such as in the Levant, Anatolia and Fars, Syriac Christianity (Church of the East) and Oriental Orthodoxy are prevalent minority denominations, which are both Eastern Christian sects mainly adhered to Assyrian people or Syriac Christians.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Vibrant indigenous minorities in West Asia are adhering to the Eastern Catholic Churches and Eastern Orthodoxy.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Saint Thomas Christians in India trace their origins to the evangelistic activity of Thomas the Apostle in the 1st century.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Significant Christian communities also found in Central Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia and East Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Islam, which originated in the Hejaz located in modern-day Saudi Arabia, is the second largest and most widely-spread religion in Asia with at least 1 billion Muslims constituting around 23.8% of the total population of Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] With 12.7% of the world Muslim population, the country currently with the largest Muslim population in the world is Indonesia, followed by Pakistan (11.5%), India (10%), Bangladesh, Iran and Turkey.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Mecca, Medina and Jerusalem are the three holiest cities for Islam in all the world.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The Hajj and Umrah attract large numbers of Muslim devotees from all over the world to Mecca and Medina.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The Druze originated in West Asia, is a monotheistic religion based on the teachings of figures like Hamza ibn Ali and al-Hakim bi-Amr Allah, and Greek philosophers such as Plato and Aristotle.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The number of Druze people worldwide is around one million.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Around 45–50% live in Syria, 35% to 40% live in Lebanon, and less than 10% live in Israel.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Recently there has been a growing Druze diaspora.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The Baháʼí Faith originated in Asia, in Iran (Persia), and spread from there to the Ottoman Empire, Central Asia, India, and Burma during the lifetime of Bahá'u'lláh.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Since the middle of the 20th century, growth has particularly occurred in other Asian countries, because Baháʼí activities in many Muslim countries has been severely suppressed by authorities.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Lotus Temple is a big Baháʼí temple in India.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Almost all Asian religions have philosophical character and Asian philosophical traditions cover a large spectrum of philosophical thoughts and writings.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Indian philosophy includes Hindu philosophy and Buddhist philosophy.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] They include elements of nonmaterial pursuits, whereas another school of thought from India, Cārvāka, preached the enjoyment of the material world.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The religions of Hinduism, Buddhism, Jainism and Sikhism originated in India, South Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] In East Asia, particularly in China and Japan, Confucianism, Taoism and Zen Buddhism took shape.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] As of 2012, Hinduism has around 1.1 billion adherents.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The faith represents around 25% of Asia's population and is the largest religion in Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] However, it is mostly concentrated in South Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Over 80% of the populations of both India and Nepal adhere to Hinduism, alongside significant communities in Bangladesh, Pakistan, Bhutan, Sri Lanka and Bali, Indonesia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Many overseas Indians in countries such as Burma, Singapore and Malaysia also adhere to Hinduism.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Buddhism has a great following in Mainland Southeast Asia and East Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The Communist-governed countries of China, Vietnam and North Korea are officially atheist, thus the number of Buddhists and other religious adherents may be under-reported.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Jainism is found mainly in India and in overseas Indian communities such as the United States and Malaysia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Sikhism is found in Northern India and amongst overseas Indian communities in other parts of Asia, especially Southeast Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Confucianism is found predominantly in mainland China, South Korea, Taiwan and in overseas Chinese populations.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Taoism is found mainly in mainland China, Taiwan, Malaysia and Singapore.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] In many Chinese communities, Taoism is easily syncretised with Mahayana Buddhism, thus exact religious statistics are difficult to obtain and may be understated or overstated.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The culture of Asia is a diverse blend of customs and traditions that have been practiced by the various ethnic groups of the continent for centuries.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The continent is divided into six geographic sub-regions: Central Asia, East Asia, North Asia, South Asia, Southeast Asia, and West Asia.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] These regions are defined by their cultural similarities, including common religions, languages, and ethnicities.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] West Asia, also known as Southwest Asia or the Middle East, has cultural roots in the ancient civilisations of the Fertile Crescent and Mesopotamia, which gave rise to the Persian, Arab, Ottoman empires, as well as the Abrahamic religions of Judaism, Christianity and Islam.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] These civilisations, which are located in the Hilly flanks, are among the oldest in the world, with evidence of farming dating back to around 9000 BCE.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Despite the challenges posed by the vast size of the continent and the presence of natural barriers such as deserts and mountain ranges, trade and commerce have helped to create a Pan-Asian culture that is shared across the region.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Rabindranath Tagore, a Bengali dramatist and author from Santiniketan (now in West Bengal, India), won the Nobel Prize in Literature in 1913, becoming the first Asian Nobel laureate.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The prize was awarded for Tagore's prose works and poetry, which had a significant additional impact on national literatures throughout the Western world.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Tagore also authored both the Indian and Bangladeshi national anthems.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Other Asian writers who won Nobel Prize for literature include Yasunari Kawabata (Japan, 1968), Kenzaburō Ōe (Japan, 1994), Gao Xingjian (China, 2000), Orhan Pamuk (Turkey, 2006), Mo Yan (China, 2012), and Han Kang (South Korea, 2024).
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Some may consider the American writer, Pearl S.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Mother Teresa of India and Shirin Ebadi of Iran were awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for their significant and pioneering efforts for democracy and human rights, especially for the rights of women and children.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Ebadi is the first Iranian and the first Muslim woman to receive the prize.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Another Nobel Peace Prize winner is Aung San Suu Kyi from Burma for her peaceful and non-violent struggle under a military dictatorship in Burma.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] She is a nonviolent pro-democracy activist and leader of the National League for Democracy in Burma (Myanmar) and a noted prisoner of conscience.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] She is a Buddhist and was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1991.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Chinese dissident Liu Xiaobo was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for "his long and non-violent struggle for fundamental human rights in China" on 8 October 2010.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] He is the first Chinese citizen to be awarded a Nobel Prize of any kind while residing in China.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] In 2014, Kailash Satyarthi from India and Malala Yousafzai from Pakistan were awarded the Nobel Peace Prize "for their struggle against the suppression of children and young people and for the right of all children to education".
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Raman is the first Asian to get a Nobel prize in Sciences.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] He won the Nobel Prize in Physics "for his work on the scattering of light and for the discovery of the effect named after him".
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Japan has won the most Nobel Prizes of any Asian nation with 24 followed by India which has won 13.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] 1933) is an Indian economist who was awarded the 1998 Nobel Memorial Prize in Economic Sciences for his contributions to welfare economics and social choice theory, and for his interest in the problems of society's poorest members.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Most of the said awardees are from Japan and Israel except for Chandrasekhar and Raman (India), Abdus Salam (Pakistan), Arafat (Palestinian Territories), Kim (South Korea), and Horta and Belo (Timor-Leste).
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] In 2006, the Bangladeshi Muhammad Yunus of was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize for the establishment of Grameen Bank, a community development bank that lends money to poor people, especially women.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] He is known for the concept of micro credit which, allows poor and destitute people to borrow money.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The borrowers pay back money within the specified period and defaulting is very low.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] Yunus also became the leader of an interim government after the 2024 Bangladesh quota reform movement.
[src:csa-group/asia-p02] The Dalai Lama received the Nobel Peace Prize, in Oslo, Norway in 1989.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] The avoidance of asthma triggers and/or allergens has been recognised by many clinicians and researchers as being an integral part of an asthma management plan.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] This report and others also assert that no single specific measure is sufficient to reduce allergens: An allergen reduction plan, which encompasses a variety of approaches is necessary to address management of asthma symptoms.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Testing is conducted at a testing facility which combines molecular biology, enzyme-linked immunosorbent assay (ELISA) with air sampling and particle counting in an environmental test chamber facility with a microbiological aerosol capability.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Standards assess products for the presence of allergenic dyes and sensitizing chemicals as well as the capacity for allergen retention and ability to withstand eradication techniques such as repeated washing machine cycles.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Product areas that have been certified include textile materials, electrical appliances, building products and kids toys.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Manufacturers must submit their products for testing to Allergy Standards Ltd approved third party laboratories.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Products must be submitted from current production and consumer ready.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] In order to pass the standards, products must meet the criteria of the standard relevant to the product category.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Certification standards are tailored to the specific product categories.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Criteria in the standards may include low or no Volatile Organic Compounds (VOC) emissions, free from banned dyes and allergens, and capable of either providing a barrier to allergens or effectively removing allergen from the environment.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Products must also demonstrate that they are capable of carrying out their function effectively and are of acceptable quality and construction.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] For example, textiles must be evaluated for barrier function, but must also demonstrate barrier function after washing.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Vacuum cleaners must demonstrate effective allergen removal, but this is also assessed when the bag is near capacity, demonstrating no significant loss of power and no redistribution of dust and allergens.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Allergy Standards Limited is an International Standards and Certification Body that prepares independent standards for products to declare their suitability for people whose lives are affected by allergies and asthma.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Their headquarters are based in Dublin, Ireland.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Allergy Standards published a white paper on Allergens and Irritants in Household Cleaning Products in the Household and Personal Care Today peer reviewed journal.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Report of the Third International Workshop.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] "Allergy Standards". allergystandards.com Allergy Standards.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] 11. “Chemical Allergens-What Are the Issues?”.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] "Allergy Standards". allergystandards.com Allergy Standards Limited.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] 19. “Allergens and irritants in household cleaning products.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] Clinical testing for triggers of asthma and allergies”.
[src:csa-group/asthma-and-allergy-friendly] *Household and Personal Care Today*, vol.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] The **BIS Hallmark** is a hallmarking system for gold as well as silver jewellery sold in India, certifying the purity of the metal.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] It certifies that the piece of jewellery conforms to a set of standards laid by the Bureau of Indian Standards, the national standards organization of India.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] India is the second biggest market for gold and its jewellery.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] India imports in excess of 1000 tons annually (including unofficially smuggled gold) with negligible local production.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] The annual gold imports are around 50 billion US$ next only to crude oil imports widening the trade deficit.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] The BIS system of hallmarking of gold jewellery began in April 2000.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] With 880.5 tons of official national gold reserves, India was globally ranked 8th in terms of national gold reserve in May 2026.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] ), lowering currency mismatch and transaction costs, and building local market infrastructure.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] Accounting for exchange rate adjustments, the dollar had experienced an approximate 11% decrease in market share since 2016, doubling that figure since 2008.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] Currency Composition of Official Foreign Exchange Reserves (COFER) survey the share of reserves held in U.S. dollars by central banks fell from 71 percent in 1999 to 59 percent in 2021.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] BIS introduced hallmarking for silver jewelry in December 2005 under IS 2112, the standard specification for 'Hallmarking of Silver Jewellery/Artefacts'.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] The testing of the jewelry as well as the hallmarking is done by approved Assaying & Hallmarking Centres present across all over nation.
[src:csa-group/bis-hallmark] These are private undertakings approved as well as monitored by the BIS.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The **Blue Angel** is an environmental label in Germany that has been awarded to particularly environmentally friendly products and services since 1978.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The owner of the label is the Federal Ministry for the Environment, Nature Conservation, Building and Nuclear Safety.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The Blue Angel is the ecolabel of the West German government and was introduced in 1978 by the Federal Minister of the Interior, which was a person of the Free Democratic Party (Germany) (FDP) in these years.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] This ministry was also responsible for environmental protection at the time, and the responsible ministers in the German federal states.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] It was established with the aim of highlighting more environmentally friendly and healthy developments and alternatives in areas where standard products have a negative impact on the environment.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] Suppliers can label their products and services with the environmental label on a voluntary basis and provide interested customers with guidance as a result.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The Blue Angel is thus a market-based, voluntary tool of environmental policy.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The logo largely corresponds to the logo of the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), although with the colours reversed.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The outer ring contains the words "BLUE ANGEL" and "THE GERMAN ECOLABEL".
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] According to the official website, it reflects the aim of the German government to embed the UNEP goals in Germany.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] In 2018 a modified version of the logo was published.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The ecolabel is only awarded to non-food products and not to food or beverages.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The Blue Angel is a so-called "Type I environmental label" according to DIN EN ISO 14024.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] This means that the entire life cycle of the product is taken into account and any impacts on the environment and health are fully considered during the development of the criteria ("multi-criteria evaluation").
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] In addition, the criteria are developed in a transparent process that includes both the suppliers affected as well as interested organisations within civil society and research institutions.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] Last but not least, the certification process is carried out by an independent body.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The Blue Angel is a member of the international network of Type I ecolabels – the Global Ecolabelling Network (GEN) – which currently comprises 29 ecolabels from various different nations.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The Blue Angel is not a label that certifies that a product is completely harmless.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The products labelled with the Blue Angel are more environmentally friendly and healthier than other products that have the same fitness for use and quality in the respective product group.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] Therefore, these products represent the "lesser evil" with respect to environmental pollution in line with the motto: as little as possible, as much as necessary.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] Specific requirements are defined for each product group.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] This means that those criteria that are relevant for the respective product group / service are selected from a broad range of possible criteria.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] (For example, the criterion "noise" is relevant for municipal vehicles but not for laundry detergents, while the opposite is true when it comes to the biodegradability of the ingredients.) The criteria and methods used to verify compliance with them are continually examined and updated.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The aim is to define criteria in such a way that the best products on the market are able to fulfil them and companies within the sector are thus encouraged to further develop their products.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] All of the criteria for the award of the environmental label to the individual product groups are published on the Blue Angel website in a transparent way.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The website also includes information on the certified products, the suppliers offering them for sale and other background information such as scientific studies and consumer information brochures.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The independent certification body – RAL gGmbH – ensures that the certified products and services comply with the relevant criteria.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] Overall, this means that the Blue Angel is not a seal of quality for the entire product but only for those characteristics of the product that have a clear impact on environmental and health protection.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] Nevertheless, the Blue Angel serves its desired function as a guide for consumers because it has quickly become a generally accepted standard on the market for environmental protection in many sectors.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] Environmental characteristics that are not stated in the basic award criteria are not tested.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] It is also possible that there are products available on the market that meet the criteria but are not labelled with the Blue Angel because it is only awarded by application.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The label only compares products with the same intended use (e.g. paper products made out of recycled fibres and virgin fibres, mechanical and chemical drain cleaners, etc.).
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] In contrast, a comparison of bicycles with motor vehicles would be like "comparing apples with oranges" because they are two completely different products that cannot be directly compared due to their different characteristics and performance specifications.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] The Blue Angel does not state which product amongst two certified products is the most environmentally friendly.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] In general, the products must avoid the use of terms such as "Bio", "Eco" or "Natural" in the product names if these products are also labelled with the Blue Angel.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] According to the criteria for the award of the Blue Angel, these advertising claims could be easily misleading to consumers especially in the case of chemical products.
[src:csa-group/blue-angel-certification] This also applies to claims that play down the risks such as "non-toxic" or "non-harmful to health".
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Bureau Veritas is present in 140 countries through a network of over 1,500 offices and laboratories, and 79,000 employees.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Bureau Veritas generated $6.34 billion in revenue in 2024.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Hinda Gharbi has been CEO of Bureau Veritas since June 2023.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] As of close of trade 20 December 2024, Bureau Veritas is a member of the CAC 40.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Bureau Veritas was founded in Antwerp, Belgium, in 1828.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Originally called the *Bureau de renseignements pour les assurances maritimes* (Information Office for Maritime Insurance), its mission was to "establish the truth and expose without apprehension or favoritism".
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Bureau Veritas provided insurers with information that enabled them to assess the reliability of ships and equipment, and to ensure the protection of people and property.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] A year after its founding, the company adopted the name "Bureau Veritas" on 28 May 1829.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In July 1833, the headquarters moved to Paris.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] To meet the needs of its clients, Bureau Veritas developed its Certification and Government services businesses to evaluate management systems and supply chains.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] It also reinforced its network and opened offices in Africa, China and the United States.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Bureau Veritas was listed on Euronext Paris on October 24, 2007.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] This initial public offering was aimed at consolidating Bureau Veritas' growth strategy by raising its profile, giving it access to new means of financing and forging loyalty among its employees.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] After its acquisition of Inspectorate in 2010, Bureau Veritas became one of the world's top three players in the commodities sector and continued to expand its geographic footprint.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] It became the leader of its sector in Canada following the acquisition of Maxxam in 2014 and carried out in parallel a series of acquisitions in the construction and consumer products industries in China.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] The 2025 strategy will be a value-enhancing journey ensuring both short and long term growth for Bureau Veritas, capturing the maximum value from the Group's existing businesses adjacent to its core activity and leading sustainability in the TIC sector.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] As of June 30, 2020, Bureau Veritas had cash and cash equivalents of €2.1 billion.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In 2020, Bureau Veritas announced a net profit of €125.3 million despite a nearly 10% drop in revenue to €4.6 billion.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Diversification of its activities has enabled the company to remain in the black despite the crisis.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In the first half of 2021, Bureau Veritas posted a net profit of €196.9 million with revenues of €2.4 billion, up 9.9 compared to 2020.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] The management is satisfied after having lost 34 million euros during the health crisis of 2020.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] These figures therefore allow the group to raise its growth forecasts for the whole of 202117.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In the same year, Bureau Veritas recruited 8,000 people, including 1,000 in France.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In March 2024 Bureau Veritas announced LEAP | 28 its latest strategy.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Based on three pillars, Portfolio, Performance and Human Capital.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In 2015, Bureau Veritas launched a strategic plan to make the Group more resilient, and more resistant to macroeconomic fluctuations (e.g. oil, gas, primary commodities, marine).
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] This strategy aims to expand the business into high-growth sectors, such as agri-food, construction and infrastructure, connected objects and automotive.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] The diversification of Bureau Veritas' activities has been accompanied by a geographical restructuring.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] The Group has expanded on its historical presence in France and Europe, reorganizing itself into three main zones: the Americas, Europe/Africa and Asia.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In December 2021, Didier Michaud-Daniel announced Bureau Veritas' ambitions for 2025, "wishing to make it a world leader on critical societal subjects such as energy transition, smart cities, new forms of mobility and traceability of supply chains".
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In 2016, Bureau Veritas entered into a strategic partnership agreement with Dassault Systèmes, which allows Bureau Veritas to use their 3DEXPERIENCE digital platform to carry out continuous assessment of ships, offshore platforms and on-board equipment throughout the entire life cycle.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In 2017, Bureau Veritas entered into a partnership with Avitas Systems a GE Venture, to launch a range of inspection services based on predictive data analytics (i.e. artificial intelligence) for all industrial sectors.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In 2018, the Group launched Origin, the very first traceability label based on blockchain technology, which provides consumers with complete, end-to-end proof of a product's journey, from farm to fork.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Bureau Veritas entered into a strategic partnership with Microsoft in 2019 to develop artificial intelligence in testing laboratories.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In January 2015, the Group expanded in China.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Bureau Veritas acquired Shandong Chengxin, a Chinese company specialized in support services for the construction of industrial infrastructure for the energy sector.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In 2017, China became the Group's largest market in terms of both revenue and employees.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In April 2019, Bureau Veritas acquired Shenzhen Total-Test, a Chinese food testing company.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Bureau Veritas aims to reach €1 billion in revenue in China by 2021.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In 2017, Bureau Veritas announced the acquisition of Primary Integration Solutions in the United States, thus expanding its Building & Infrastructure business into data centers.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In March 2018, the Group expanded into the construction sector in the United States with the acquisition of EMG.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] This expansion continued even further with the acquisition of Owen in 2019, a provider of compliance services for buildings and infrastructure.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In Europe, Bureau Veritas acquired Q Certificazioni, an Italian organic food certification body, in 2019.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] The very same year, with the integration of Capital Energy in France, Bureau Veritas expanded its consulting and assistance services in the field of energy efficiency certification.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In January 2021, Bureau Veritas takes a majority stake in cybersecurity specialist Secura.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In April 2021, the company acquires Bradley Construction Management, an American society specialized in project management and construction management services for the renewable energy sector.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In September 2021, Bureau Veritas acquires AET France, a company specializing in laboratory testing, product development and sustainability testing.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In January 2022, Bureau Veritas acquires PreScience specialized in Project Management and Construction management services for Transportation Infrastructure projects.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In June 2022, Advanced Testing Laboratory, specialized in scientific sourcing services, is acquired by Bureau Veritas.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In July 2022, Bureau Veritas acquires AMSfashion, an expert in sustainability, quality and conformity services for the fashion industry.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] Bureau Veritas' board of directors is made up of twelve members.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In December 2022, Laurent Mignon was appointed on the board of directors succeeding André François-Poncet.
[src:csa-group/bureau-veritas] In June 2023, Laurent Mignon is appointed Chairman of the Board of Directors and Pascal Lebard is appointed Lead Independent Director and Vice-Chairman of the Board of Directors.
[src:csa-group/cebec] In 2004 it was audited by an international team and at the end of 2004 the SGS CEBEC laboratory was approved as a CBTL (CB Testing Laboratory) under the international IECEE-CB scheme.
[src:csa-group/cebec] In 2005, it was approved by EEPCA as a laboratory operating in compliance with the CCA, HAR and ENEC agreements.
[src:csa-group/cebec] Mark of compliance with Belgian safety standards.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] The **CSA Group**, formerly known as the **Canadian Standards Association** (**CSA**), is a standards organization which develops standards in 57 areas.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] CSA publishes standards in print and electronic form, and provides training and advisory services.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] CSA is composed of representatives from industry, government, and consumer groups.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] CSA began as the **Canadian Engineering Standards Association (CESA)** in 1919, federally chartered to create standards.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] During World War I, lack of interoperability between technical resources led to the formation of a standards committee.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] CSA is accredited by the Standards Council of Canada, a crown corporation which promotes voluntary standardization in Canada.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] This accreditation verifies that CSA is competent to carry out standards development and certification functions, and is based on internationally recognised criteria and procedures.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] The CSA registered mark shows that a product has been independently tested and certified to meet recognized standards for safety or performance.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] During World War I, lack of interoperability between technical resources led to frustration, injury, and death.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Britain requested that Canada form a standards committee.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Sir John Kennedy, as chairman of the Civil Engineers' Canadian Advisory Committee, led the investigation into the necessity of an independent Canadian standards organization.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] As a result, the Canadian Engineering Standards Association (CESA) was established in 1919.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] CESA was federally chartered to create standards.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] At the beginning, they attended to specific needs: aircraft parts, bridges, building construction, electrical work, and wire rope.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] The first standards issued by CESA were for steel railway bridges, in 1920.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] In 1927, CESA published the Canadian Electrical Code.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Enforcing the code called for product testing, and in 1933, the Hydro-Electric Power Commission of Ontario became the sole source for testing nationwide.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] In 1940, CESA assumed responsibility for testing and certifying electrical products intended for sale and installation in Canada.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] CESA was renamed the Canadian Standards Association (CSA) in 1944.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] The certification mark was introduced in 1946.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Known in the French-language as *Association canadienne de normalisation*, CSA used the French-language acronym of **ACNOR**.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] The initialism "CSA" is now used in both official languages.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] In the 1950s, CSA established international alliances in Britain, Japan, and the Netherlands, to expand its scope in testing and certification.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Testing labs were expanded from their first in Toronto, to labs in Montreal, Vancouver, and Winnipeg.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] In the 1960s, CSA developed national occupational health and safety standards, creating standards for headgear and safety shoes.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] By the late 1960s and early 1970s, the CSA began to expand its involvement in consumer standards, including bicycles, credit cards, and child resistant packaging for drugs.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Tom Pashby became chairman of the CSA in 1975, serving for two decades to set standards for manufacturers of ice hockey helmets and lacrosse helmets.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] In 1984, CSA established QMI, the Quality Management Institute for registration of ISO9000 and other standards.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] In 1999, CSA International was established to provide international product testing and certification services while CSA shifted its primary focus to standards development and training.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] In 2001, these three divisions were joined under the name *CSA Group*.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] In 2004, OnSpeX was launched as the fourth division of CSA Group.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] In 2008, QMI was sold to SAI-Global for $40 million.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Most standards are voluntary, meaning there are no laws requiring their application.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Despite that, adherence to standards is beneficial to companies because it shows products have been independently tested to meet certain standards.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] The CSA mark is a registered certification mark, and can only be applied by someone who is licensed or otherwise authorised to do so by the CSA.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] CSA developed the CAN/CSA Z299 series, now called N299, of quality assurance standards, which are still in use today.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] They are an alternative to the ISO 9001 quality management standard, specific to companies supplying goods to nuclear power plants.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Currently forty percent of all the standards issued by CSA are referenced in Canadian legislation.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] CSA has developed many relevant standards in the electrical field, including the **Canadian Electrical Code (CEC)**.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] **CSA C22.2 standard** for *Rigid Types EB1 and DB2/ES2 conduit, ENT tubing*, to clarify and unify the installation specifications for cables and electrical conduits and to regulate the manufacturing, performance, and marking of PVC conduits.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] Laws in many jurisdictions in North America require that certain products be tested for standards compliance by a body officially recognized for that purpose.
[src:csa-group/csa-group] CSA Group is accredited to do so in a variety of areas by the SCC in Canada and OSHA in the United States (as a Nationally Recognized Testing Laboratory).
